<br>
I would love to see more of the culture played out as well.<br>
<br>
The iksar seem to be pretty well done from what I have seen. You have the loyalists and the rest are pretty much outcast and treated as such.<br>
<br>
Dwarvish and gnomish culture goes the same way.<br>
<br>
The other races need a little work though (as a whole, individually this can't be done).<br>
<br>
I would like to see more distinction between the Wood Elves and High Elves. At one time they were one culture. Now they are not, but are played almost as if they are the same race. Both commonly follow Tunare, but I think that is where the similarities stop. Wood Elves are typically more uncivilized and sometimes barbaric in comparison to the High Elves. For example, an enemy is captured. The High Elves would probably opt for life imprisonment. The Wood Elves would probably kill the prisoner (not torture, they are barbaric, not evil, though in some cases they might, they are not evil, but not always good either). Wood elves are also distrustful of strangers and probably indifferent at best to their High Elf cousins (think they are snobby, or strayed from Tunare's true teachings). This is their culture as a whole, not the individual. A wood elf in say, Freeport might be the friendliest person you will ever meet, or the worst (depending on their reason for leaving the forest, those that are different then themselves are outcast in some cases).<br>
<br>
Ogres and Trolls are too commonly dependent on the dark elf or evil human culture. Trolls are not smart, but are smart enough to have some sort of an empire at one time (don't quote me on this one, I know they warred with the ogres at one point). Even before LoY I see alot of trolls in evil guilds that are ran by humans or dark elves. I expect this is mostly from the lack of trolls actaully played though. And wasn't their a troll guild? The same goes for Ogres, I know they were cursed, but I wouldn't mind seeing more and more of the ogre culture be apparent, rather then being mindless warriors used by the smarter races. Not saying anything is wrong with the current system, individually, we want to join X guild that just happens to have a so and so race as leader.<br>
<br>
Barbarians seem to do well with their culture, even when they work with others, they look down on the southrons.<br>
<br>
Frogloks, haven't seen much here. Not even sure what the culture is, never been to Gukta( or grobb oops hehe).<br>
<br>
Humans are numerous and adapt very well to anything. But they do in fact have their own culture. Lots of pontential here. They have so many relegions as well. What I would like to see is more relegious or philosophical debates between the same aligned characters. A Paladin of Mithaniel Marr will not always agree with a Paladin of Karana or even Rodcet Nife (gods maybe allies, but the church probably preached that their god is better then any other). Same with Shadowknights, Bertox SKs will probably not even get along well at all with Inny SKs. Spreading hate is duty, but catching a disease is not, and since they are evil aligned, sometimes they would be hostile to one another. This all applies to Erudites, which would see any other race as beneath them.<br>
<br>
Half elves don't typically have their own culture, they just do whatever they prefer.<br>
<br>
I don't know much about the halfling culture in EQ, in D&amp;D(3rd) they fall under the Half elf category as far as culture goes.<br>
<br>
And I don't know much about Vah Shir. Only been to Shar Vahl like twice.<br>
<br>
These suggestions are by no means telling anyone how they should play their character. But is a nice attempt to show a guildline of the cultures (as I see them and think we need more of, you might see different). Individual characters can and usually do stray from these examples. They are adventurers, not merely citizens. Though many a guild could use these examples to help set a theme within the guild. Or you could use as a background to a SL. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=falinoralastrarran>Falinor Alastrarran</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Soulfood!</span><br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/11/03 11:44 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm42.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=337.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://thealastrarranhome.nstemp.net/SolufeinIcon.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Some thoughts on RP for FV</span><hr size=1> I really don't think the RP community has diminished in size...I just think it has become too localized to here and there. There exist a great many little clique's of RP that are often times guild limited.<br>
